 Arch linux
&lt;/a&gt;
 installation is not that hard if you do it simple as if:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;you don&amp;rsquo;t need dual boot and just want to install it as first OS on your drive.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;your computer is not too old and it supports &lt;a href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Partitioning#GUID_Partition_Table" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"&gt;
 GPT
&lt;/a&gt;
, &lt;a href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Unified_Extensible_Firmware_Interface" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"&gt;
 UEFI
&lt;/a&gt;
, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;you don&amp;rsquo;t need LVM, system encryption or &lt;a href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/RAID" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"&gt;
 RAID
&lt;/a&gt;
.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;you don&amp;rsquo;t mind to read the wiki pages.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;See also: &lt;a href="https://wiki.archlinux.org/title/Installation_guide" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"&gt;
 Official Installation Guide
&lt;/a&gt;
